{{About|the lover of Sappho|the country|Miletus}}
'''Anactoria''' (or '''Anaktoria''') is the name of a woman mentioned by poet [[Sappho]] as a lover of hers in [[Sappho's Fragment 16]] (Lobel-Page edition) [http://www.sacred-texts.com/cla/sappho/sappho0.htm], often referred to by the title "To an Army Wife, in [[Sardis]]". [[Sappho 31]] is traditionally called the "Ode to Anactoria", though no name appears in it (A. C. Swinburne, quoted in Lipking 1988).
[[Algernon Charles Swinburne]] wrote a long poem in ''[[Poems and Ballads]]'' titled ''Anactoria'', in which Sappho addresses Anactoria in imagery that includes [[sadomasochism]], [[cannibalism]], and [[dystheism]].[http://www.letrs.indiana.edu/cgi-bin/acs-idx.pl?type=section&rgn=level1&byte=97791] Lipking (1988) discusses Swinburne's poem.
