{{redirect|Pouffe|the hairstyle|pouf}}
[[File:Little Miss Muffet 1940 poster.jpg|thumb|1940s poster promoting reading among children, depicting [[Little Miss Muffet]] sitting on a tuffet]]
A '''tuffet''', '''pooffer''', or '''hassock''' is a piece of furniture used as a [[footstool]] or low seat. It is distinguished from a [[Stool (chair)|stool]] in that it is completely covered in cloth so that no legs are visible, and is essentially a large hard cushion that may have an internal wooden frame to give it more rigidity.

Wooden feet may be added to the base to give it stability, at which point it becomes a stool or a footstool. If the piece is larger, with storage space inside it, then it is generally known as an [[Ottoman (furniture)|ottoman]].{{r|TheFreeDictionary.com}}

The term ''hassock'' has a special association with churches, where it is used to describe the thick cushions (also called [[kneeler|kneelers]]) employed by the congregation to kneel on while in prayer.

==Etymology==
[[File:Salisbury Cathedral, Hassocks.jpg|thumb|Hassocks stacked up in [[Salisbury Cathedral]]]]
The names ''tuffet'' and ''hassock'' are both derived from English names for "a small grassy [[hillock]] or clump of grass", in use since at least the sixteenth century. The word ''tuffet'' comes from [[Anglo-Norman language|Anglo-French]] {{lang|xno|tuffete}}, from *''tufe'' "tuft".{{r|Merrian-Webster online}} The first known use of the word ''tuffet'' was in 1553.{{r|Merrian-Webster online}}

''[[Chambers 20th Century Dictionary]]'' does not recognize the use of "tuffet" for a piece of furniture,{{r|Chambers}} and the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' says that it only "perhaps" means hassock or footstool, suggesting that this usage is due to a misunderstanding of the nursery rhyme "[[Little Miss Muffet]]".{{r|OED online}}

''Pouffe'' is a nineteenth-century French import for "something puffed out".

